## Step 4: Clone Zed Repository

### 4.1 Choose a Location
Pick a folder with at least 25 GB free space. For example:
```
D:\Projects\
```

### 4.2 Open PowerShell
Navigate to your chosen folder:
```powershell
cd D:\Projects
```

### 4.3 Clone the Repository
```powershell
git clone https://github.com/zed-industries/zed.git
cd zed
```

**Time:** 5-10 minutes (repository is ~2 GB)

---

## Step 5: Build Zed

### 5.1 Open PowerShell in Zed Directory
Make sure you're in the `zed` folder:
```powershell
cd D:\Projects\zed
```

### 5.2 Choose Build Type

**Option A: Release Build (Recommended)**
- Slower to compile (45-90 minutes)
- Optimized, faster runtime performance
- Smaller executable size

```powershell
cargo run --release
```

**Option B: Debug Build**
- Faster to compile (30-60 minutes)
- Slower runtime performance
- Larger executable size
- Better for development/debugging

```powershell
cargo run
```

### 5.3 What to Expect During Build

You'll see output like:
```
Updating git repository `https://github.com/...`
Compiling proc-macro2 v1.0.0
Compiling unicode-ident v1.0.0
Compiling serde v1.0.0
...
Building [===============>       ] 1149/1560
...
Finished release [optimized] target(s) in 52m 34s
```

**Progress indicators:**
- `Updating git repository...` - Downloading dependencies
- `Compiling xyz v1.0.0` - Building individual crates
- `Building [=====>  ]` - Progress bar
- `Finished release [optimized]` - BUILD COMPLETE! ✅

### 5.4 Build Time
- **First build:** 45-90 minutes
- **Subsequent builds:** 5-15 minutes (only changed files recompile)

### 5.5 Find the Executable

After successful build:
- **Release:** `target\release\zed.exe`
- **Debug:** `target\debug\zed.exe`

### 5.6 Run Zed
```powershell
.\target\release\zed.exe
```

